<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Tries to Find Solution to Niger Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The military leader who will step down on May 29 said here
before the closed door meeting that " I have called this meeting
for us to finally discuss and find lasting solutions to the
problem of the Niger Delta."
</P>
<P>
After the expiration of an ultimatum on Monday to the oil
companies operating in Niger Delta area, the youths from 61 jaw
communities seized five barges , four tugboats and one sea track
belonging to oil companies.
</P>
<P>
The onslaught against oil companies in the region took a new
dimension last Wednesday when the militant youths took over 13
flow stations.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued by the Association of Mobil Spill
Affected Communities, seven flow stations belong to Shell in the
Batan area and the other six in the North Bank oil companies
started after a 40,000 barrels spill took place at Idoho Oit on
January 12 , 1998 , affecting large area of the Niger Delta
region.
</P>
<P>
After paying 20,000 Naira (about 222 U.S. dollars ) to some
victims, Mobil is said to have refused to pay the rest of the 2
billion Naira (about 22 million dollars ) compensation demanded
by the affected communities.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year , Nigeria's oil production has been
seriously affected by intermittent disturbances caused by local
youths demanding a greater share of the region's oil revenue for
impoverished farming and fishing communities.
</P>
<P>
Multi-national companies operating joint ventures with
state-run Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation say that a
lasting solution should be founded to solve the dispute in order
to maintain normal oil production in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
