<HEADLINE> 5 Confirmed Dead, 41 Injured in Train Collision in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- At least five people have been
confirmed dead and 41 others injured Saturday evening in a train
accident in northern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
A security source told the country's Middle East News Agency
that the number of casualties are still being counted, saying that
the injured have been rushed to hospitals in Mansoura, Shirbin,
Belkas and Talkas and Talkha in the Nile Delta.
</P>
<P>
The trains hit each other head-on at 17:45 local time (1545
GMT) at Shirbin station, about 130 kilometers northeast the
Egyptian capital, Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations show that the accident was caused by
a signal operator who failed to stop one of the trains, the news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations are under way to retrieve passengers from
four carriages that were destroyed in the crash.
</P>
<P>
Shirbin is a town on the main line between Cairo and Damietta
at the northeastern edge of the Nile Delta.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's railways have suffered a series of major accident in
the past four years. Last November, 47 people were killed when a
train jumped its tracks near Kafr el-Dawar, a Delta town 30
kilometers southeast of the Mediterranean port of Alexandria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
