<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Saudi Arabia and Lebanon have concluded an agreement
to form a joint business council to develop bilateral economic and
trade ties, London-based Arabic Al Hayat newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the end of a meeting attended
high-ranking economic officials of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The American oil companies operating in Egypt covers
35 percent of total area of the country, Oil Minister Hamdi Al
Banbi has said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. oil companies have invested some 14 billion
U.S. dollars and produce 55 percent of the country's total
oil output, 35 percent of the total natural gas, the Al Hayat
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran announced Saturday that an Italian company will
invest 120 million dollars in the construction of two tunnels in a
freeway linking Tehran with the northern Iran.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Tehran-Shomal Freeway Company Mostafa Miri
said that the investments will be used for importing drilling
and ventilation equipment as well as technology for Talun and
Kandovan tunnels in the Tehran-Shomal (north) freeway route.
</P>
<P>
Miri put the total length of Talun and Kandovan tunnels
at 22 kilometers and said the projects are to be implemented
within five years, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Ministry of Industries said Saturday that the
country's cement production increased by 4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some 19.7 million tons of clinker and 20.1 million tons of
cement were produced last year, registering a 4 percent increase
in terms of weight from 1997, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry estimated the value of country's exportable
cement during the current Iranian year starting March 21 at 50
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Minister of Industries Gholamreza Shafei put the
country's annual cement production capacity at 23 million tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
