<HEADLINE> 4 Dead, 42 Injured Confirmed in Train Collision in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Four killed and 42 injured persons
in a train collision have been sent to hospital in northern Egypt
on Saturday evening, a Shirbin hospital official said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports quoting police said the train collision near
Shirbin station in northern Egypt left at least 25 people dead and
25 others injured. And the Egyptian Ministry of Interior has
confirmed the accident.
</P>
<P>
The trains hit each other head-on near Shirbin station, about
130 kilometers northeast of the Egyptian capital, Cairo, police
said.
</P>
<P>
The official at Shirbin Hospital said under condition of
anonymity that the hospital received four corpses and 42 injured
people, of whom six were referred to another hospital for lack of
beds.
</P>
<P>
Shirbin is a town on the main line between Cairo and Damietta,
at the northeastern edge of the Nile Delta.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian railways have suffered a series of major accidents in
the past four years. The most serious was in December 1995 when
two trains collided in fog south of Cairo, killing 75 people and
injuring 76.
</P>
<P>
Last November, 47 people were killed when a train jumped its
tracks near Kafr el-Dawar, a Delta town 30 kilometers southeast of
the Mediterranean port of Alexandria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
