<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Train Collision Kills 25, Injures 25 Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Two trains collided in northern
Egypt Saturday evening, killing at least 25 people, police said.
</P>
<P>
Another 25 people were wounded in the crash, which occurred in
Shirbin, 130 kilometers northeast of the Egyptian capital, Cairo,
police said.
</P>
<P>
The trains hit each other head-on near Shirbin station, police
said. Shirbin is a town on the main line between Cairo and
Damietta, which is at the northeastern edge of the Nile Delta.
</P>
<P>
The police said that the casualties might be higher than the
figure announced as rescue work is still going on.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents, including train crash with heavy casualties
are common in Egypt. In November, 47 people were killed when a
train was derailed near Kafr el-Dawar, a Delta town 30 kilometers
southeast of the Mediterranean port of Alexandria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
