<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Head Distressed at Assassination of Nigerien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), Salim Ahmed Salim, Saturday
expressed his "great shock" over the brutal assassination of
President Ibrahim Bare Mainassara of Niger.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Salim said that "I am extremely
distressed over the prevailing situation of uncertainty in the
Republic of Niger."
</P>
<P>
Salim also expressed his concern over "an attempt to bring
about political change violently and through unconstitutional
means," appealing to all political and military leaders as well as
the people of Niger to " remain calm in this difficult period of
their national history."
</P>
<P>
He recalled "the decision of OAU Heads of State and Government
during their 33rd Ordinary Session in Harare, Zimbabwe in June
1997, where they took a stand against unconstitutional changes of
government, and declared such changes unacceptable and
inconsistent with Africa's quest for democratization of the
continent."
</P>
<P>
"I wish in particular to urge the political leaders of Niger to
engage in immediate consultations and dialog in order to ensure
that the laid down constitutional procedures are followed, in
resolving the political crisis that has resulted from the
president's assassination," Salim said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The OAU head also hoped that the people of Niger "will endeavor
to overcome their current crisis and ensure that their country is
returned to the path of constitutional rule and that they will be
able to chart the future through a democratic process."
</P>
<P>
Late President Mainassara was killed in an ambush by coup
soldiers at the Niamey Airport Friday. He was elected as President
of Niger in July 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
