<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Macedonia Appear to Resolve Name Issue Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- After seven years of dispute
between Greece and Macedonia, the two neighbors appeared to settle
the thorny name issue over Macedonia this month.
</P>
<P>
Greece had agreed to recognize Macedonia under the name
Republic of Macedonia-Skopje, the Athens daily "The Tribune"
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis and
Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov would sign the necessary
agreement in New York on April 25.
</P>
<P>
Greece opposes the use of the name "Macedonia" by the former
Yugoslav republic, saying that it implies territorial ambitions
over its own northern region of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Greece imposed a trade embargo over Macedonia and
claimed that relations between the two countries could not be
normalized until the name issue was resolved.
</P>
<P>
Trade ties between Greece and Macedonia have in recent years
been improved significantly, with Athens now becomes the largest
direct investor in Macedonia, which declared independence in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
