<HEADLINE> Li Peng Conferred Pakistan's Highest Civil Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of China, was
conferred here on Saturday "Nishan Pakistan," the highest civil
award of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani President Rafiq Tarar conferred the award on Li Peng
in the President's House in recognition of Li's "most valuable
contribution to the cause of promoting understanding, friendship
and cooperation" between Pakistan and China.
</P>
<P>
The citation, read out by A.W. Qazi, Federal Cabinet Secretary
of the Pakistani government, said Li Peng is "an old friend of
Pakistan and has made a very significant contribution to
strengthening the bilateral relations between Pakistan and China,
which has earned him deep appreciation and respect of the
Government and the people of Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Before the award presentation, Li Peng paid a courtesy call on
President Tarar. The two leaders agreed to further promote the
existing friendly and cooperative relations between the two
"fraternal countries."
</P>
<P>
Tarar expressed his sincere thanks to China for its constant
support and assistance to Pakistan in various fields.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it was especially important for the two
countries to further strengthen the bilateral relations in today's
world where profound changes are taking place.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the two countries should maintain their high-level
contacts and exchanges, Tarar said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng agreed with Tarar, saying that the high-level exchanges
between Pakistan and China is an important component of the
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz
called on Li Peng and they held brief but friendly talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
