<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Face Unprecedented Drought, Officials Warn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Senior Iranian officials have
warned that Iran would face an unprecedented drought this year,
the most serious one in the past 30 years, as rainfall in the
country falls sharply.
</P>
<P>
"The country is expected to experience water shortages this
year," Deputy Energy Minister for Water Affairs Gholamreza
Manuchehri said on Saturday, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the amount of rainfall in Tehran's watershed
zones has dropped by 50 percent from the figure of last year and
by 20 percent compared to the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
However, water consumption has increased by 4 percent annually
in Tehran over the past 10 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Agriculture Minister Isa Kalantari on Thursday also
warned that the country would face a shortage of 1.2 billion
cubic meters in water resources for agricultural uses this year.
</P>
<P>
He said at least 15 percent of fertile agricultural lands
located by the Sefidroud river in the agricultural province of
Gilan would not be cultivated this year due to shortage of
water in the Sefidroud Dam.
</P>
<P>
The Aras Dam in Ardebil province and Sefidroud Dam saved water
behind them only to 30 and 60 percent of their capacities
respectively, he said, adding that the dry farming lands of
Ardebil province in northwestern Iran have been completely
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Kalantari called on farmers to adopt measure to reduce their
water consumption and said drilling of deep wells, which has
already started in Gilan province, could help solve the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
