<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, WTO Discuss Kingdom's Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Ministers of Trade and
Planning held separate talks Saturday with a visiting delegation
of the World Trade Organization (WTO) on Riyadh's access to the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Press Agency (SPA) monitored here said Trade Minister
Ussama Faqih reviewed with the WTO delegation the outcome of talks
a Saudi delegation recently held in several western countries
concerning the issue.
</P>
<P>
A Saudi delegation visited Belgium, the United States, Canada
and Japan last month, where they discussed with concerned
local officials the principles and requirements for Saudi Arabia
to become a member state of the WTO.
</P>
<P>
In his talks with the WTO delegation, Saudi Planning Minister
Dr. Abdulwahab Attar discussed the steps and procedures undertaken
by the Gulf kingdom regarding its trade policies.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has concluded, during the past four years, five
rounds of negotiations with the WTO on the country's accession to
the organization.
</P>
<P>
The WTO has been requiring Saudi Arabia to be flexible in its
trade policies to ensure conformation with the terms of
membership.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Saudi officials expect that their
country would become an effective member of the WTO before the end
of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
