<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Condemns Assassination of Nigerien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Executive Secretary of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), Lansana
Kouyate, has strongly condemned the assassination of Nigerien
President Ibrahim Bare Mainassara.
</P>
<P>
A statement by the Nigeria-based organization quoted Kouyate as
decrying ''this act of violence, and any attempt to seize power
through the use of arms.''
</P>
<P>
Mainassara was killed in an ambush by soldiers at the Niamey
Airport Friday following weeks of electoral dispute in the west
African country of some 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
Peace, progress and development can only be achieved "through a
peaceful and democratic transition process," the ECOWAS leader
noted.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to politicians, the army and the people in Niger to
"unite in ensuring that their country does not fall into a spiral
of violence which can only have negative repercussions for the
populace."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the executive secretary "is in constant
touch with the ECOWAS chairman, President Gnassingbe Eyadema of
Togo, who is monitoring events in Niger with close attention."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Secretary-General of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim are
among world leaders who have expressed concern over the
assassination, considering it a set back to democracy on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nigerien government reportedly reopened the land
borders Saturday in a fresh sign of normalization one day after
the "unfortunate incident" as it described.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for the assassination remained unclear. But the
military sources said that those who killed the president were in
control behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Saturday said that Niamey, capital of the
former French colony was calm with state radio broadcasting Moslem
religious chants in keeping with a one-month declared period of
national mourning for late President Mainassara, who himself
seized power in a military coup in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
