<HEADLINE> Blair Says Russia, NATO "Must Agree to Disagree" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Saturday Russia and Nato will have to agree to disagree
over the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We simply have to accept differences of opinion (with Russia)
over NATO action," Blair told reporters outside his country
residence, Chequers, where he held talks with Spanish Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar.
</P>
<P>
Blair spoke shortly after Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
told his British counterpart, Robin Cook, in a 45-minute telephone
call that Russia had no intention of becoming involved in any
confrontation in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"They (the Russians) understand very well the action that we
are taking," he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said Russia posed no threat to NATO
countries despite their differences over NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He again ruled out that NATO would send ground troops into
Kosovo to stop Yugoslavia's drive against ethnic Albanians in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Air attacks alone were working and, while all options were
always kept under review, NATO believed its strategy of not
calling in ground forces was right, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a British Foreign Office spokesman said that Cook
assured Ivanov that NATO's action posed no possible threat to
either the security or peace of Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Like Russia we would welcome a political settlement (in
Yugoslavia). But it has got to be one that enables the refugees to
return in safety under international protection," Cook was quoted
by the spokesman as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
