<HEADLINE> Opposite Voice Growing, Schroeder Defends NATO Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN April 10 (Xinhua)--Amid protest in several cities on
Saturday against NATO air raids and growing doubts inside his
ruling coalition, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder defended the
western military operations.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 people Saturday rallied in the northern city of
Hamburg to protest against NATO air strikes on Yugoslavia. The
demonstrators carried placards reading " Stop The War" and "
Withdraw German Forces".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the western industrial city of Stuttgart, about
5,000 people held anti-war demonstration against NATO's hardline
policy in Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
About 50 sitting-in demonstrators blockaded until late Saturday
afternoon the gate of Spangdahlem air base, where thirteen U.S.
F-117 Stealth fighters were stationed for bombing Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"In the final analysis we will be proven right and we will
achieve our goals," Shroeder told the press, adding, "You can not
counter genocide in Yugoslavia with pacifist positions."
</P>
<P>
A special congress of Schroeder's Social Democratic Party (SPD)
was scheduled for Monday, when the traditionalists of the party
were expected to propose a new political solution to Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The pacifist Environment Minister Juergen Trittin of the Greens
Party, the junior partner sharing power with SPD, also expressed
his concern about the effectiveness of the NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
Trittin called for NATO to review its strategy of military
operations, saying, "I can not understand why a heating plant in
Belgrade or civilian installations in Montenegro are being
destroyed." 
</P>
