<HEADLINE> Liberia Denies Backing S. Leone Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government Saturday
rejected the accusations by commander of the west African
peace-keeping force of ECOMOG, Major General Felix Mujakpero,
that it allowed shipment of heavy arms to the rebels in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Information Minister Joe Mubah dismissed as empty
alarm the involvement in the supply of heavy arms to the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) by the Liberian government,
according to a report reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
General Mujakpero said in Sierra Leonean capital Freetown
Friday that a Ukrainian-registered cargo aircraft carrying 68 tons
of arms arrived in Burkina Faso and the arms were later
transported to the RUF rebels through Liberian territory.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG force which is mandated to support the Sierra
Leonean government threatened "to strike at all the channels
involved in the movement of heavy arms and ammunitions to the
rebels by land, sea and air."
</P>
<P>
The Liberian government has consistently denied supporting the
rebels in the tiny west African country, but countries including
the United States and Britain have backed accusations against it.
</P>
<P>
The nine-year-old conflict in Sierra Leone has resulted a death
toll of more than 20,000 people and forced some 500,000 refugees
to flee to neighboring states. 
</P>
