<HEADLINE> Pentagon Announces More Planes for NATO Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon announced
Saturday that 82 U.S. planes would join airstrikes over Yugoslavia
in a move to intensify the battle against Serb forces while Allies
were expected to add dozens more aircraft within days.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokeman Kenneth Bacon said that the addition of these
aircraft will help "expand the number of strikes over any
24-hour-day period." They also provide "more deep strike capacity
as necessary. So, basically it will allow us to increase the
intensity of the air campaign over Kosovo and Yugoslavia," he
added.
</P>
<P>
It could take a month for 24 Apache attack helicopters to
arrive in Albania. Their introduction would mark an escalation of
the war and for the first time allow close-to-the-ground, direct
strikes against Serb troops and tanks during persistent bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon also raised the possible need for the president to
call up military reserves because of the additional U.S. aircraft
joining NATO's campaign.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military began moving equipment to Tirana, the
Albanian capital, this weekend in advance of the Apaches, which
will fly there from Germany. But bad weather canceled several of a
few dozen flights.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 150 C-17 cargo planes that will transport the
Apache-related equipment to Tirana must compete with hundreds of
flights carrying humanitarian supplies for more than 500,000
ethnic Albanian refugees who have fled Kosovo. Only one C-17 at a
time can land at Tirana's airfield.
</P>
<P>
NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark requested the Apaches two
weeks ago. They were approved by the Pentagon April 3 and by NATO
on Monday along with a support package of 18 long-range multiple
rocket launchers, two dozen support helicopters, Bradley Fighting
Vehicles and about 2,600 U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said at first the helicopters and support package
would arrive in Albania within 10 days. But the military officials
said Saturday only a few Apaches might be ready then and it could
take 30 days for all 24 Apaches to become operational.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials said Clark does not yet need the gunships,
which are vulnerable to the Serbs' still robust anti-aircraft
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen signed Clark's request
Saturday, calling up planes from U.S. bases as well as Atlantic
and Pacific commands to join NATO airstrikes within "a matter of
days," said Charles Wald, a strategic planner for the Joint Chiefs
of Staff. Bacon said allies would add more in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. aircraft include 24 F-16CJ fighters, four A-10
"tank killer" aircraft, six EA-6B Prowlers that have radar-jamming
abilities, 39 KC-135 refueling tankers, two DC-10 tankers and
seven C-130 cargo planes.
</P>
<P>
The deployment will bring the U.S. aircraft contribution to
about 480 warplanes out of a total NATO force of nearly 700,
according to Bacon.
</P>
<P>
Meantime, congressional criticism continued against President
Clinton for refusing to consider using ground troops if necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
