<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Opposition Opposes Govn't Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The opposition National
Constitutional Assembly said here Saturday that it has completed
the drafting of a proposed legal instrument it wants in place
before taking part in the constitutional reform process.
</P>
<P>
Legal task force chairman of the opposition party, Welshman
Ncube said that an extraordinary general meeting of the party
would be held in Harare next Wednesday to discuss the draft before
it was presented to the government.
</P>
<P>
Ncube said this at a party meeting convened to explain why it
turned down the government's invitation to participate in a
commission which would be appointed by President Robert Mugabe to
redraft the constitution.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed commission provides for a people-centered and
comprehensive review of the constitution of Zimbabwe and its
eventual adoption through a national referendum," the Zimbabwe
News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
This would provide for the establishment, powers and functions
of the national consitutional commission.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the commission would be irrevocable and it
would be composed of the 150 members of parliament and not less
than 250 various other stakeholders in the country which include
religious groups and opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The opposition party had argued that it was inappropriate to
proceed with the constitutional reform process under the
provisions and terms of Commissions of Inquiry Act, which formally
repose excessive powers on the state president on both the process
and the result.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, participants at the meeting were unanimous that the
organization should not join the presidential commission until the
legal framework has been put in place.
</P>
<P>
They were also confident that if the party remains resolute,
the government would give in to its demand for the legal
framework.
</P>
<P>
They said opposition parties must mobilize all Zimbabweans to
reject the method the government wanted to review the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The government has said it will go ahead with the process of
redrafting the constitution with those willing to participate.
</P>
<P>
However, it did not reveal the names of the people who had
confirmed to participate in the commission as promised this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
