<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Open Final Postponed to Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The final of the 350,000-US-
dollar Salem Hong Kong Open was halted by rain Sunday night and
postponed to Monday with third seed Andre Agassi of the United
States leading Germany's Boris Becker 2-0 in the decider.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, the only non-German player in the last four and seeking
his first title of the year, fought to 6-7 (4-7), 6-4 with a
stubborn Becker in the first two sets.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that a Hong Kong Open final is to be
played on Monday. The last time was the 1997 final between
American Michael Chang and Australian Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
Agassi conceded no more than three games in every set he played
in the tournament before entering the final, which had been
delayed for over five hours due to intermittent rain after only
two points were played in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, who had filed divorce with actress Brook Shields, said
he entered the Hong Kong event and next week's Japan Open because
of the need to "play more tennis." Becker anticipated the chances
are 50-50.
</P>
<P>
Agassi beat Germany's Henrik Dreekmann while Becker outplayed
countryman Bernd Karbacher in the semis to reach the final.
</P>
