<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda's Major Opposition Demands Pardon for Role in Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda's major opposition party,
the Republican Democratic Party (MDR), has publicly asked for
pardon and apologized for its role in the killings which rocked
Rwanda in the 1960s and culminated into the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
''The MDR demands pardon to all Rwandans for divisive teachings
 by some of its leaders which became the basis of the Hutu
''power'' (faction) and which led them into the 1994 genocide and
massacres,'' Prime Minister Pierre Celestin Rwigema, was quoted
Saturday by the Rwanda News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
''The MDR party re-affirms that those teachings are against the
 principles of democracy and republic of the party,'' he further
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The MDR party condemned some of its leaders who spread the
''genocidal'' teachings and promised to help the government to
bring them to court.
</P>
<P>
The party, also as well as the prime minister, announced
sweeping reforms of the party which buried the past Hutu extremist
ideology of its god- father, the MDR-PALIMEHUTU -- the party for
the emancipation of the Hutu people, which began the massacres of
Tutsis in 1959, and the year which followed.
</P>
<P>
As indicated by Rwigema, reforms within his party began in May
1998 with the setting up of a commission in charge of the
restructuring of the party's statutes, its interpretation of the
history of Rwanda, as well as its flag.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that late last month, a new executive committee
was set up in a special convention which adopted changes.
</P>
<P>
The MDR therefore distanced itself from its god-father the MDR-
PALIMEHUTU and shun for ever the divisive teachings of the past.
It changed its statutes and shifted its colours from the red-black
flag to the red-green one.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, the red stood for the blood of the MDR fighters
who spilt their blood to liberate the country from the oppression
of Tutsis and colonists, while black meant ''four centuries'' of
darkness and oppression in which the Tutsis had kept the Hutus.
</P>
<P>
According to Rwigema, the colour red stands for the blood of
all Rwandans which was spilled at all times, and even during the
genocide, while green represents hope for the new reconciled and
unified Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The reforms within the MDR party are in line with other global
changes of all items recalling the tragic past of Rwanda, like the
national anthem, the national flag, and the court of arms, the
names of streets and places which were inspired by the same
divisive ideology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reports 7 Years' Negative Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
financial and manufacturing center, has reported negative
population growth for seventh consecutive year, the municipal
government announced today.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, Shanghai had 13.075 million people with
residence cards and 14.64 million permanent residents. Birthrates
for permanent residents were 5.2 per thousand in 1998, and the
death rate was 7 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
The city has 7 million fewer people than what demographers
estimated before 1963, when the city introduced its family-
planning policy. The success in controlling population growth has
been attributed partly to 1998's per capita GNP, which is equal to
3,400 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city now faces the challenge of solving the problems caused
by a rapidly aging population, as one out of every 6 of its people
is above the age of 60 and it is estimated that the elderly will
account for up to 37 percent of Shanghai's people by the year 2030.
</P>
<P>
In addition, one study has shown that 0.98 percent of the
children below the age of 7 are handicapped. Shanghai has been
making an effort to deal with these problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
