<HEADLINE> Iran Protests Iraq over Assassination of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday lodged strong
protest with the Iraqi government about its support for the
Iranian outlawed Mujahideen Khalq Organization (MKO) which
assassinated a senior Iranian commander Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry summoned the Iraqi charge
d'affaires to Tehran to make the protest, the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's Director General on Persian Gulf, Ali-Asghar
Khaji, told the Iraqi envoy that such events would leave negative
and irreparable impacts on Tehran-Baghdad relations.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Iraqi government to offer its explanations on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chief of the joint staff of Iranian armed forces
Brigadier General Ali Sayyad Shirazi was gunned down by
unidentified persons Saturday morning as he left home for work.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-based MKO later claimed responsibility for the
killing and said that Shirazi was targeted because he was
responsible for purging and executing military personnel, and
responsible for the death of hundreds of thousands of teenagers
in the war with Iraq (1980-88).
</P>
<P>
Shirazi, born in 1944, served as commander of the Iranian
army's ground forces during the Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday morning, Iranian Majlis Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq
Nouri and Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi
also slammed the western countries for supporting the MKO.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said those countries, which sheltered the terrorist MKO,
unfortunately encouraged them to commit such crimes by refraining
from adopting serious stands against them.
</P>
<P>
If such countries were really sincere in dealing with
terrorism and the terrorists, they should take practical and open
measures to cope with the terrorists to satisfy the world public
opinion, he said.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, one of the main political groups which toppled former
Iranian shah regime, fled into Iraq after it was outlawed in 1981
due to sharp difference with the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
The MKO has claimed responsibility for several assassinations
and bombings inside Iran during the past decades. In retaliation,
the Iranian armed forces also bombed the MKO bases in Iraq
several times.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly accused Baghdad of supporting the MKO,
which Tehran termed as a "terrorist" group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
