<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Draw Called as New Rule Ushered in at Judo Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- No draw is called and overtime is
frequent in the National Women's Judo Championships here as
organizers were expecting more exciting bouts in the domestic
competition.
</P>
<P>
Judokas who tied in the four-minute regular game are carried
into the overtime, in which the athlete who scores first or has
her opponent penalized wins the match.
</P>
<P>
"This change forces players to put up more attacking strategies,
" said Song Zhaonian, vice president of the Chinese Judo
Association. "Matches became more attractive under the new rule."
</P>
<P>
The sport of judo is not popular in China though it may has
origin in Chinese martial art. Only dozens of audiences watched
the top-level national tournament at the Guilin Sports Stadium in
Guilin, the capital city of Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Three judges handling a bout take the role to decide the winner
of a match by vote in the international and Olympics competitions
after competitors are tied in the fight.
</P>
<P>
But it is not always easy to draw out the more aggressive side
when a bout is fairly a match-up.
</P>
<P>
"Sometime it is really difficult to grand the victory to player
who fights harder and better in a close match," said Song, who
worked as a judge at the Bangkok Asian Games last December.
</P>
<P>
"The no-draw rule is also a great hit to those judokas who ask
for judges' favor on out-of-competition reasons."
</P>
<P>
Coaches and team officials seems to welcome the change in rule.
</P>
<P>
A Beijing coach said, "My players fought more aggressively in
this tournament than before."
</P>
<P>
Team leader of the Jiangsu Province said, "We always tell our
players to fight hard. We have no difficulty adapting to the new
rule." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
