<HEADLINE> ABCs Of Macao SAR's Basic Law (23) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 7 in a question
and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Will MSAR Government departments be responsible to
corresponding Central People's Government departments?
</P>
<P>
Although the MSAR is a local administrative region directly
under the Central People's Government, it enjoys a high degree of
administrative autonomy and has the power to handle local
administrative affairs on its own in accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
MSAR departments are not responsible to the corresponding
Central People's Government departments. MSAR Government
departments are only responsible to the Chief Executive of the
MSAR, who is responsible to both the Central People's Government
and the MSAR, in accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a high degree of autonomy in the MSAR, Article 22 of
the Basic Law states that Central People's Government departments
and provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities directly
under the Central People's Government can not interfere in MSAR
administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
If they wish to set up offices in the MSAR they must obtain the
consent of the MSAR Government and get approval from the Central
People's Government.
</P>
<P>
Offices set up in the MSAR by Central People's Government
departments, or by provinces, autonomous regions, or
municipalities directly under the Central Government and the
personnel of these offices must abide by the laws of the Region. (
more)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABCs Of The Macao SAR Basic Law (24) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 24 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Will the National Security Law apply to the MSAR?
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, only national laws listed in Annex
III to the Basic Law are to apply to the MSAR. The National
Security Law is a national law on independence, unification, and
security, but, because it is not listed in Annex III it does not
apply to the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
Macao has long had a capitalist economy and its way of life and
values are different from those of the mainland. But, it is an
administrative region of China and has the obligation to safeguard
China's independence, unification and security. The law is not
listed in Annex III but this does not mean that there is no need
to safeguard national unification and security in the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
Article 23 of the Basic Law says that the MSAR is to enact laws
on its own to prohibit acts of treason, secession, sedition, or
subversion of the Central People's Government, or the theft of
state secrets, or foreign political organizations from conducting
political activities in the Region, and political organizations in
the region from establishing ties with foreign political
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The article says that the MSAR can enact laws on its own that
cover acts that endanger China's independence, unification, and
security. The enactment of these laws is an obligation of the MSAR
to China, and must proceed in accordance with the provisions of
the Basic Law
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
