<HEADLINE> U.S. Regrets India's Test-firing of Agni-II Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States Sunday
expressed regret over India's test-firing earlier in the day of
Agni-II, an extended range version of medium-range ballistic
missile.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the U.S. embassy in New Delhi said the
U.S. believed "concrete restraints by India would create a more
positive atmosphere for improving relations among the various
countries concerned and for addressing international
non-proliferation issues."
</P>
<P>
Information and Broadcasting Minister Pramod Mahajan announced
on Sunday that India "successfully launched" a Agni-II missile at
10:00 a.m. (0430 GMT) from Wheeler island in Balasore District,
east state of Orissa.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy statement expressed the hope that India would
provide tangible indications that it was prepared to practice
restraint consistent with its declared intentions.
</P>
<P>
The missile was test-fired exactly 11 months after India
conducted nuclear tests on May 11 last year, indicating an end of
a five-year restraint since the country test-fired its
1,500-km-range Agni-I in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Moscow, a Russian official expressed concern at
the arms race in South Asia in close vicinity of Russia and its
CIS allies in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said almost immediately
after the announcement of the test-firing that Islamabad might
give a "befitting response" to the latest test-firing by India.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern at the test-firing, saying it "introduces
a new weapons system in the subcontinent" and "obviously it is a
matter of concern" for Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, Japan's foreign ministry said in a statement that the
test-firing threatened regional stability.
</P>
<P>
"It is truly regrettable that India conducted a missile testing
on April 11 despite the repeated requests made by Japan against
it," said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
