<HEADLINE> Iran Protests Iraq Over Assassination of Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday lodged a strong
protest to the Iraqi government for its support of the Iranian
outlawed Mujahideen Khalq Organization (MKO) which assassinated a
senior Iranian commander on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry summoned the Iraqi charge
d'affaires to Tehran to listen to the protest, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's Director General on Persian Gulf Ali-Asghar
Khaji told the Iraqi envoy that such events would leave negative
and irreparable impact on Tehran-Baghdad relations.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Iraqi government to offer its explanations
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chief of the joint Staff of Iranian armed forces
Brigadier General Ali Sayyad Shirazi was gunned down by
unidentified persons at 0645 hours local times (0215 GMT) as
he left home for work.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-based MKO later claimed responsibility for the
killing and said Shirazi was targeted because he was
responsible for purging and executing military personnel, and
responsible for the deaths of hundreds of thousands of
teenagers in the war with Iraq (1980-88).
</P>
<P>
Shirazi, born in 1944, served as commander of the Iranian
army's ground forces during the Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday morning, Iranian Majlis Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq
Nouri and the Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza
Asefi also slammed the western countries for supporting the
MKO.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said those countries, which sheltered the terrorist
MKO, unfortunately encouraged them to commit such crimes by
refraining from adopting serious stands against them.
</P>
<P>
If such countries were really sincere in dealing with
terrorism and the terrorists, they should take practical and
open measures to cope with the terrorists to satisfy the
world public opinion, he said.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, one of the main political groups which toppled
former Iranian shah regime, fled into Iraq after it was
outlawed in 1981 due to sharp difference with the Iranian
government.
</P>
<P>
The MKO has claimed responsibility for several assassinations
and bombings inside Iran during the past decades. In retaliation,
the Iranian armed forces also bombed the MKO bases in Iraq
several times.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly accused Baghdad of supporting the MKO,
which Tehran termed as a "terrorist" group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
