<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Arrest Cheats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Five Zambian government officials,
a Senegalese national and some street vendors have been arrested
in connection with a racket making and uttering false road
licenses.
</P>
<P>
The arrested government officials are from the Anti-Corruption
Commission (ACC), Government Printers, Road Traffic Commission
(RTC) and the Road Safety Council, Sunday Times of Zambia
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to a police report, others involved in the racket are
a Senegalese national and some street vendors in Lusaka, the
capital, and Ndola and Kitwe in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
The officials were arrested on the charge of making and
uttering false documents and obtaining a large amount of money by
false pretenses.
</P>
<P>
All the accused are expected to appear in court soon.
</P>
<P>
The government has lost billions of kwacha (millions of U.S.
dollars) in the racket, over which Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi
recently raised concern because of the RTC's failure to meet
expected revenue targets from the sale of road licenses.
</P>
<P>
Out of an expected 10-billion-kwacha revenue for the first
quarter licences, only one billion kwacha was realized.
Investigations into the matter were made when it was discovered
that many motor vehicles were displaying fake versions of the road
licenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
