<HEADLINE> Bomb Blast Injures Four Ugandans in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Four people were injured in a
bomb blast near Kakivubo Stadium in downtown of Uganda's capital,
Saturday evening, Police Spokesman Bog Ngobi told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview Sunday morning in Kampala, Ngobi said:
"One was seriously injured in the blast and all the four injured
were rushed to Mulago hospital for treatment immediately after
police arrived at the scene."
</P>
<P>
"I'm not sure whether there were more injuries. But only four
were injured by last evening. We have not made any arrest nor
have we established the motivation behind the explosion," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Evening commuters and soccer lovers scampered for cover when an
 explosive device ripped through a shopping area around the New
Taxi Park.
</P>
<P>
Alice Namugabo, 48, who came to visit her daughter, lost her
left eye.
</P>
<P>
Police soon cordoned off the area and preliminary
investigations had found a shattered time device that indicated
the explosive was an improvised time bomb.
</P>
<P>
Security sources suspected that the bomb was originally
intended to go off during or shortly after the Uganda-Tunisia
match in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
This is the second blast that happened in the capital city this
year. On February 14, the Valentine's Day celebrations were
violently interrupted by two bomb blasts at a suburb of
Kabalagala. Six died and scores more were injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
