<HEADLINE> Nigerian President-elect Condemns Coup Plot in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian president-elect Olusegun
Obasanjo has condemned the killing Friday of the president of
Niger Republic, saying it was out of tune with current democratic
trend worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure for Asia in continuation of his on-going
world tour, Obasanjo noted "military coups anywhere in the world
are out of fashion and the coup in the Niger Republic is
unfortunate and a setback for democracy and the people of Niger,"
The Post Express reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Assassinated Nigerien leader Lbrahim Bare Mainassara will be
buried Sunday in his home village of Doumesa, two days after he
died in a hail of bullets at a military camp outside capital
Niamey last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Talks between Niger's military and political leaders began in
Niamey at the weekend on the turn of event in the country. And
Col. Moussa Moumouni Djemakoye, the army's chief of staff, and
Major Dauda Mallam Wanke, head of Niger Republic's presidential
bodyguard, were widely considered potential candidates to become
the country's next leader.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria shares a 1,500-kilometer border with the Niger
Republic.
</P>
<P>
During his Asian tour, Obasanjo is scheduled to visit China,
Japan and India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
