<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Decides to Cut Ties With IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Zimbabwe Africa
National Union Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF) decided at its last
politburo meeting in capital Harare to cut ties with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank after
repeated trips to Washington for support over the past few months
yielded nothing, the Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
Natan Shamuyarire, ZANU-PF secretary for information and
publicity, who is also Minister of Industry and Commerce, told the
Sunday Mail that after careful consideration, the party had
decided that Zimbabwe should seek alternative sources of funding
its programs.
</P>
<P>
Both the IMF and the World Bank, major backers of Zimbabwe's
economic reforms for the past seven years, had made unrealistic
demands on the Zimbabwean government as a prerequisite for
releasing balance of payment support and financing energy
development projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF was against the country's land acquisition program and
the involvement of Zimbabwe in the conflict in the Democratic
Republic of Congo, while the World Bank had said the Zimbabwean
government should decide on one project between the Gokwe and
Hwange power projects.
</P>
<P>
Sahamuyarire said the government would seek alternative sources
of funding for balance of payment support.
</P>
<P>
He said the ruling party decided that the government should go
ahead with the development of both the Gokwe North Power Station
and the extension of Hwange Thermal Power Station without the
World Bank risking guaranteeing loans.
</P>
<P>
He assured industry and commerce that the country and its
economy would survive without the IMF's 53-million-U.S. dollar
standby facility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
