<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Research On Genetic Disease (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- China's strategy to make disease-
related genetic research the center of its Human Genome Project (
HGP) is the correct course, according to one of HGP's major
researchers.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have cloned genes that cause hearing loss
and exostosis, an abnormal bony growth on the surface of a bone,
and have made progress in research on leukemia and cancer of the
esophagus, liver, and nasopharynx area.
</P>
<P>
Some research findings have been reported in scientific
journals like Nature, Nature Genetics, and Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences of the United States, according to
Professor Chen Zhu, the director of a national HGP center in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The findings are expected to benefit health studies and the bio-
pharmaceutical industry in the next century, he says.
</P>
<P>
Global HGP research started in the United States in 1990. In 2
or 3 years scientists will try to identify all 100,000 human genes
and interpret their genetic codes. Only a small part of these
genes are useful to the study of disease, but they have enormous
potential for the pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
When China's HGP program began some 5 years ago, researchers
had little technology and funding and decided not to follow the
path of their western counterparts who intended to map and
sequence all human genes, a multi-billion-dollar project which
could match the moon-landing program in scale.
</P>
<P>
China's HGP strategy was mainly to identify disease-related
genes to make use of China's advantages to develop genetic weapons
against major illnesses, Chen explains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Research on Genetic Disease (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The advantage he refers to is China's large amount of genetic
resources because of its numerous ethnic groups living separately.
</P>
<P>
While cancer, respiratory diseases, cerebral vascular illness,
and heart disease are the major killers in China, depression,
hypertension, diabetes, and diseases of the elderly pose new
threats. Some illnesses with particular high incidences in China,
such as cancer of the liver, esophagus, and nasopharynx passages,
viral hepatitis and some hereditary diseases are pushing
scientists to look for gene-based therapies.
</P>
<P>
Unlike in the past, China's HGP is getting increased policy and
financial backing. There have been HGP centers in Shanghai and
Beijing since last year that focus on identifying and cloning
genes related to liver cancer, diabetes, high blood pressure and
other diseases. Some 30 laboratories are also involved in the
sequencing and analysis of human genes.
</P>
<P>
Chen and his colleagues are increasing genetic material
collections of DNA samples and establishing more cell lines. Last
year, the government restricted the removal of human genome
resources from China and began encouraging Sino-overseas
cooperation in genetics with shared intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that we can find 1,000 disease-related genes by the
year 2001, and identify and clone the functional genes linked to 5-
to-10 major diseases," Chen says.
</P>
<P>
"A report in Nature last year described China's human genome
research as 'set to take off'," he says, "now the challenge for us
is how far we can fly." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
