<HEADLINE> Taliban Rule Out New Talks With Rivals This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Taliban militia have ruled
out the possibility of a new round of peace talks this month with
the rival northern alliance, the Associated Press of Pakistan
(APP) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Abdul Hai Muttmain, the Taliban's senior official
responsible for information, APP said in a report from Afghanistan
that the U.N.-sponsored peace talks last month was a failure as
the opposition has been on the offensive on the battlefield since
then.
</P>
<P>
Abdul said the Taliban's Supreme Council will decide whether to
continue peace talks with the northern-based alliance, but
certainly not this month.
</P>
<P>
"Only our supreme council can decide to resume talks with the
opposition. And it has not yet given the permission," said Abdul
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the last round of talks held in the Turkmen capital
Ashgabad, the two Afghan warring factions agreed to hold a second
round of talks inside Afghanistan at a mutually-agreed date.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. had hinted that the new round of talks will be held in
April.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to form a broad-based government to
restore peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
But soon after the talks, fighting started between the two
rivals on several fronts with each accusing the other of flouting
the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
