<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels Free Second Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The National Democratic Front
(NDF) on Sunday freed a Philippine army officer in Surigao del
Sur, the Southern Philippines, two days after it released a
policeman, Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Army Sgt. Alipio Lozada was freed by the New People's Army
(NPA), the armed wing of the NDF, in an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Lieutenant General Angelo Reyes, army
commander in the south, as saying that Lozada was turned over by
NPA operators to a group of humanitarian peace mission, which
facilitated the release.
</P>
<P>
"With the release of Lozada, we are looking forward for the NPA
to set free (Brig.) General victor Obillo and Capt. Eduardo
Montealto," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lozada was captured by elements of the New People's Army after
an encounter near Tandag, Surigao del Sur, on March 5.
</P>
<P>
He is the second captive released by the New People's Army
within a week. The first was Chief Insp. Roberto Bernal who was
freed in Sorsogon Friday after 47 days of captivity.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the NDF described Lozada's release as a
confidence-building measure and said it would pave the way for its
resumption of peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
During the last two months, the New People's Army abducted four
police and army officers, in addition to the one captured by the
group last year, demanding exchange of prisoners of war with the
government.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada suspended indefinitely peace talks
with the NDF last month after the abductions took place.
</P>
<P>
After negotiations by a third group led by church leaders, the
NDF promised to release all the five by April 19.
</P>
<P>
The government has welcomed the NDF move and expressed its
readiness to resume peace talks with the rebel group if it
releases all the hostages safely. 
</P>
