<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Raps the West for Supporting Outlawed Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday lashed out at the
western countries for supporting the country's outlawed Mujahideen
Khalq Organization (MKO) after it assassinated a senior Iranian
military commander.
</P>
<P>
"You (the west) give refuge to the criminal terrorists, let
them in your parliaments, collect signatures in their support and
call yourselves advocates of human rights and opponents of
terrorism, what else would you have to say now?" Iranian Majlis
(Parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri was quoted by the
Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces Brigadier General
Savad Shirazi was gunned down by unidentified men in northern
Tehran Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-based MKO has claimed responsibility for the killing,
saying Shirazi was targeted because he was held accountable for
purging and executing military personnel, and for the death of
hundreds of thousands of teenagers in the war with Iraq in 1980 to
1988.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi also
expressed regret over the "contradictory stands of some western
countries on the evil phenomenon of terrorism and the
contradiction in their beliefs and performance."
</P>
<P>
Expressing abhorrence towards the MKO's terrorist act in
killing the Iranian commander, Asefi said those countries, who
sheltered the terrorist group MKO, unfortunately encouraged them
to commit such crimes by refraining from adopting serious stands
against them.
</P>
<P>
If such countries were really sincere in dealing with
terrorism and terrorists, they should take practical and open
measures in this regard to satisfy the world public opinion, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that there was no longer any
justification for some western countries to neglect the MKO
terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
Shirazi, born in 1944, served as commander of the Iranian
army's ground forces during the eight-year Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, a main armed Iranian opposition group, has claimed
responsibility for several assassinations in Iran, including the
killing of Assadollah Lajevardi, the former head of Iran's
Prisons Organization last August.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, also a main political group which had fought against
the former Iranian shah regime, was outlawed in 1981 due to sharp
differences with the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
During the past decades, the MKO launched various attacks on
Iranian targets inside and outside Iran. In retaliation, the
Iranian armed forces also bombed the MKO bases in Iraq several
times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
