<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO "Turning The Screw" On Milosevic: Cook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The latest NATO deployments in the
Balkans are intended to "turn the screw" on Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We are pilling on the pressure," Cook told the BBC. "We can
keep going longer than his war machine can."
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that unity among the NATO allies had
strengthened as the air campaign lengthened.
</P>
<P>
Cook insisted that Yugoslav forces were being weakened by NATO
attacks, saying Serbian forces were low on fuel and communication
centers had been hit so hard that field commanders now had to
communicate by mobile phone.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of ground forces being sent in to impose a
peace, Cook said it would take two to three months to assemble
such a force.
</P>
<P>
"A ground war would involve a lot more casualties than the air
campaign on both sides. I think those who are perhaps rather
lightly calling for ground troops should reflect whether they
would still support it once the casualties started to mount," he
said.
</P>
<P>
It is believed here that Britain will almost double its forces
committed to Kosovo with the announcement Sunday that the aircraft
carrier Invincible is to be deployed off the coast of Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
