<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Deeply Concerned over India's Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Sunday promptly
reacted to an Indian missile test and said it was deeply concerned
over the fresh action by India.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistani Foreign Office spokesman said India's development
of Agni-II missile, an intermediate range ballistic missile,
introduces a new weapon system in the region which is "naturally a
matter of deep concern for Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
He said India was continuously engaged in massive acquisition
of weaponry from all sources in addition to its large indigenous
production and that the Indian armament acquisitions are
aggravating the conventional imbalance which already exists
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The development of Agni-II adds to our concerns and threat to
our security," the spokesman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
India said it successfully test-fired Agni-II missile at 10:00
a.m. (0430 GMT) on Sunday from Wheeler island in Balasore
District, east state of Orissa.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the 20-meter long missile, with a range of
2,000 kilometers and capability to carry either conventional or
nuclear warheads, can strike any target in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan also complained that India failed to provide it timely
and sufficient information in advance.
</P>
<P>
"We were informed about the test only two days ago in response
to an inquiry by our High Commissioner in New Delhi. While
confirming their intention to test, the Indian side did not
provide information about the time or date for the test," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) signed
in Lahore in February this year obliged the two countries to
provide advance notification to each other in the event of a
planned test.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question, the spokesman said Pakistan is
obliged to maintain a deterrence in the interest of its security
and peace and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
"Our indigenous missile program is part of this deterrence," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
