<HEADLINE> Turkish President Leaves for Albania, Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said here Sunday that Turkey will expend all efforts to
overcome the problems Albania and Macedonia are facing.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at Ankara airport before leaving
for the two countries, Demirel said that his one-day visit will
stress the solidarity of Turkey with Kosovar refugees who are in
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that "I believe that my visit is a timely opportunity
to show the support we extend to them and to stress the importance
Turkey attributes to the stability and tranquility of Albania
which we have perfect relations in the Balkans."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president said that he will discuss coordination
of humanitarian aid which Turkey started during the meetings with
the leaders of Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Demirel will visit the camps of Kosovar refugees and get
information about the works underway during his trip in the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that today's most important problem was to
provide the transitory sheltering for refugees under the best
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Massive exodus of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, a Serbian
province in Yugoslavia, started following the U.S.-led North
Atlantic Treaty Organization unleased fierce air strikes against
Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
NATO wanted to bomb the Yugoslav government into accepting a
peace deal with separatist ethnic Albanians and allowing foreign
troops to be stationed in Kosovo to enforce the agreement.
</P>
<P>
More and more Kosovar refugees are streaming into neighboring
Albania and Macedonia, causing a grave humanitarian crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
