<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Enact Law to Protect Local Musicians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will
enforce the copyright law to protect Kenyan music industry from
being exploited by the media and entertainment agencies, Kenyan
Information and Broadcasting Minister Joseph Nyagah has revealed.
</P>
<P>
Nyagah said the government measures would cover music played
by the Kenyan Broadcasting Corporation (KBC) and other
broadcasting houses which owed the local industry a lot of money,
the Herald newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Nyagah urged broadcasting houses and entertainment agencies to
pay musicians royalties as they were making enough money to pay
them.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Music Copyright Society of Kenya (MCSK) accused
Media Owners Association for failing to pay their annual fee
totalling 120 million shillings (nearly two million U.S. dollars)
it owed the music industry.
</P>
<P>
However, the KBC denied immediately that it owed the society of
millions of shillings.
</P>
<P>
"The money the radio and entertainment agencies make is enough
to pay musicians promptly on time. There is no reason why the
musicians should not be paid on time," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Musicians end up suffering because some people don't want to
pay them royalties. This should stop," Nyagah said.
</P>
<P>
He commended the MCSK for its efforts in trying to eliminate
and control piracy in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
