<HEADLINE> Australia Hails U.S.-China Trade Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Australia welcomes the trade
breakthrough made by China and United States over the weekend, a
leading Australian official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tim Fischer, Australian Deputy Prime Minister and Trade
Minister, said the trade deal moved China a step closer to joining
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"These new Chinese offers are of great potential value to
Australian exporters and point the way to acceptable outcomes for
the unresolved trade issues of importance to Australia, which
include access for sugar and wool," the deputy prime minister said
in a statement received by Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"I will pursue these outstanding issues when I visit China next
month," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Fischer said he expects China now to move
progressively to resolve outstanding issues with other WTO members,
including Australia, so that China could enter the WTO later this
year.
</P>
<P>
"(The Australian federal) Cabinet this week authorized me to
push ahead with Australia's negotiations with China, and I remain
hopeful of a successful outcome when I visit China next month," he
said in a separate statement last week, commenting on the progress
made China and the United States in their trade talks.
</P>
<P>
He said he was encouraged by the details of the U.S.-China
trade pact, including improved market access for agriculture,
industrial tariff cuts, information technology and services.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued over the weekend, U.S. President
Bill Clinton and visiting Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, said the U.S.
supports China's accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
They undertook that further negotiations designed to solve the
remaining trade issues between the two countries would be
concluded by the end of this year, paving the way for China's
accession by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
