<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 07:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Businessman Released on Bail in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The German businessman Helmut
Hofer, who was sentenced to death in Iran for illegal sexual
relationship with a Muslim woman, was released on bail from
prison Saturday night, an Iranian judicial official announced on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The release came hours after German special envoy and
Chancellery Minister Bodo Hombach arrived here Saturday morning to
discuss Hofer's case and bilateral relations with Iranian
officials.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder last November appointed
Hombach as his special envoy in charge of Hofer's case and Bonn
has repeatedly called on Tehran to set Hofer free.
</P>
<P>
Director of Public Relations Office of the Iranian Judiciary
Fotowat Nassiri Savadkouhi told the Islamic Republic News Agency
that Hofer was released on a bail of 500 million rials (about
166,000 U.S. dollars) pending the convening of his next court
session.
</P>
<P>
However, Hofer will not be allowed to leave Iran until his
trial reopens, the official said, but he did not disclose the
exact date of retrial.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was arrested in September, 1997 at Tehran international
airport upon his arrival from Germany with an Iranian woman who
was waiting for him. He was sentenced to death by a local court in
Tehran for illicit sexual relationship in January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to Iranian law, non-Muslim men are forbidden to have
any sexual relations with Muslim women. Hofer appealed the court
ruling by claiming that he had converted to Islam before meeting
the Iranian woman.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Supreme Court in December rejected the sentence on
Hofer and returned the case to local court for retrial.
</P>
<P>
Iran on Thursday announced to grant a release on bail to the
57-year-old German businessman with the consideration of the need
for further investigation and the period Hofer has been jailed.
</P>
<P>
Germany has been Iran's biggest trading partner, but their
relations have been strained since April, 1997 after a Berlin
court accused Iranian leaders of sponsoring terrorist
assassinations against Iranian dissidents in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The death sentence against the German businessman blocked a
rapprochement between Tehran and Bonn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
