<HEADLINE> Post-Jordan Bulls Slumps to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chicago Bulls earned a
place in the NBA history books as they were held to the lowest
point total since the advent of the shot clock by the Miami Heat
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls, six-time NBA champions in the 1990s with retired
Micheal Jordan leading the way, became the first team since the
advent of the shot clock in 1954 to fail to break 50 points,
suffering a humiliating 82-49 loss to the Heat.
</P>
<P>
The post-Jordan Bulls also set an NBA record for fewest baskets
made with just 18. They shot a woeful 23 percent (18-of-77),
including 0-of-9 from 3-point range, and made only 13-of-24 free
throws.
</P>
<P>
In the laugher Miami scored the game's first 15 points and
things just got worse for Chicago, which managed a mere eight
points in the first quarter and 10 in the third.
</P>
<P>
In Phoenix, rookie Pat Garrity scored 25 points and Cliff
Robinson added 22 as the Suns hammered San Antonio Spurs 110-84 to
cut their six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
In Sacramento, Chris Webber posted his league-leading 32nd
double-double of the season with 23 points and 11 rebounds as the
Kings beat the Denver Nuggets 110-104.
</P>
<P>
At Indiana, Bobby Phills hit a 15-foot jumper with 39 seconds
left to lift the Charlotte Hornets to a 92-90 win over the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
In Los Angeles, Rasheed Wallace scored 19 points off the bench
to lead four Portland players in double figures as the league-
leading Trail Blazers fought back with their smothering defence to
record a 97-70 rout of the league-worst Clippers.
</P>
<P>
In Cleveland, Shawn Kemp had 24 points and 12 rebounds and the
Cavaliers shut down the Atlanta in the first quarter on the way to
a 81-67 victory over the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
In Dallas, Terry Cummings sank the go-ahead jumper with 35
seconds left and blocked Gary Trent's potential winning shot at
the buzzer as the Golden State Warriors held on for a 91-90
victory over the Mavericks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
