<HEADLINE> India Testfires Agni-II Ballistic Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- India successfully test-fired
advanced Agni-II, an intermediate range ballistic missile (IRBM),
Information and Broadcasting Minister Pramod Mahajan announced
here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Describing it as "a historic feat," Mahajan said the extended
range IRBM was "successfully launched" at 10:00 local time on
Sunday from Wheeler island in Balasore District, east state of
Orissa.
</P>
<P>
The missile was test-fired exactly 11 months after India
conducted nuclear tests on May 11 last year, indicating an end of
a five-year restraint since the country test-fired its
1,500-km-range Agni-I in 1994.
</P>
<P>
An official spokesman said that India took neighboring Pakistan
into confidence about the test firing as under the "Lahore
Declaration" signed between prime ministers of the two countries
last February, both had agreed to inform each other before
test-firing any missile.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the India government had informed Pakistan about
its plan to test-fire Agni-II missile, Mahajan said.
</P>
<P>
However, Pakistan's Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said almost
immediately after the announcement of the test firing that
Islamabad might give a "befitting response" to the latest
test-firing by India.
</P>
<P>
Agni, a re-entry missile system which goes into stratosphere
before coming down on its target, is capable of carrying both
conventional and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The 20-meter long missile, weighing 16 tons, is capable of
carrying a 1,000-kg warhead.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the test-firing has established
critical technologies associated with design, development and
production of long range missile system.
</P>
<P>
Agni-II is part of India's integrated guided missile
development program, other versions include surface-to-surface
"Prithvi", surface-to-air "Aakash" and "Trishul", and anti-tank
"Nag". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy Predicted to Grow 4 Pct in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines should expect to
see significant gross national product (GDP) growth this year from
3.5 to 4 percent, presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Subic, about 80 kilometers north of
Manila, Barican attributed the significant growth to the
"pump-priming" activities the government has been undertaking over
the previous months to create "a very vital factor to the
Philippine economy."
</P>
<P>
To prove his point, Barican quoted Budget Secretary Benjamin
Diokno as saying that among the countries affected by the currency
crisis that began in mid-1997, the Philippines was not as affected
as the rest of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
But due to the effect of the crisis and bad weather, the
country's GNP only grew 0.1 percent in 1998, while its gross
domestic product shrank by 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Barican said that the government is concentrating on bringing
back investor confidence to the country to prevent net losses in
businesses here.
</P>
<P>
Barican also said the administration of the Subic Bay
Metropolitan Authority, which oversees the development of the
55,000-hectare freeport land area, is doing a good job towards the
government's aim of attracting foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Subic, a former U.S. navy base, became a special economic zone
in the early 1990s after the U.S. withdrawal. It now serves as a
showcase of the country's economic reform success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
