<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> About 300,000 Drug Addicts in Sri Lanka: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- There are some 300,000 Sri
Lankans fell victim to narcotic drugs and 8 billion rupees (114
million U.S. dollars) go to the pockets of drug dealers annually,
according to the latest study.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the Sri Lanka Anti-Narcotics
Association, said most drug addicts are within the age group of 16
to 25.
</P>
<P>
There are fears whether the lower limit is dropping still
further. At times 13-year-olds have been in the racket, according
to the study.
</P>
<P>
Police Narcotics Bureau said that out of about 300,000 drug
users in the country, nearly 100,000 are heroin inclined while the
rest are prone to use cannabis, an indigenous product more
popularly known as ganja.
</P>
<P>
The first user of heroin in Sri Lanka was detected in 1980. The
predominant method of abusing is inhaling the vapors of heated
heroin.
</P>
<P>
There have been 10,170 cases of heroin detection in the country
during 1998 while it was 4,888 for cannabis.
</P>
<P>
The International Narcotics Control Board said in its annual
report for 1998 that a significant amount of heroin is brought in
Sri Lanka from India in boats by traffickers operating between
southern India and the western coast of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
During the 1997, 30 percent of heroin supplied to Sri Lanka had
been from India while 42 percent was from Pakistan. The balance 28
percent had come from other sources.
</P>
<P>
However, in 1998 supplies from India shot up to 71 percent
while those from Pakistan constituted only three percent.
</P>
<P>
At present there are 10 treatment centers for drug users in the
country out of which four are run by the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
