<HEADLINE> Sun Loses Japan Open Final to Gade Christensen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Sun Jun of China failed to extend
his head-to-head winning record against Peter Gade Christensen as
the Danish retained the men's singles title at the Japan Open
badminton tournament on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sun, who defeat the Denish defending champion at the Copenhagen
Masters in December and the Grand Prix Final in February, bowed to
Gade Christensen 3-15, 10-15.
</P>
<P>
Sun was slow to adapt to the variety shots of Gade Christensen
who combined his soft-touched drops with an array of powerful
smashes to take the lopsided first game.
</P>
<P>
Sun, ranked fourth in the world, tried to change the pace,
moving the Dane around the court by hitting under-hand net shots
and drives in the second game.
</P>
<P>
But Sun found few chances to go back into the game as the
Denish defender kept his momentum to record a 11-3 lead before he
fired a smash to Sun's backhand to finish off the 37-minute match.
</P>
<P>
Sun said: "I had a fair wind in the first game and I couldn't
hit hard, allowing him to hit smashes. I got used to it in the
second game, but it was too late as I was already 4-11 down."
</P>
<P>
With the victory, which brough the winner a check of 14,400 U.S.
dollars, Gade Christensen reduced his record against Sun to three
wins against four defeats.
</P>
<P>
The women's singles champion went to China's Ye Zhaoying who
beat her compatriot Gong Zhichao 1-11, 11-5, 11-6.
</P>
<P>
In Mixed doubles final, China's pair Liu Yong and Ge Fei
overwhelmed the South Korean pair Ha Tae-Kwon and Chung Jae-Hee 15-
1, 15-3 for the title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
