<HEADLINE> India's Foreign Exchange Reserves Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- India's foreign exchange
reserves increased by 949 million U.S. dollars during the week
ending on April 1, thus pushing the total foreign exchange
reserves to the highest ever levels of 32.53 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The increase is mainly due to a rise in the foreign currency
assets which grew by 960 million dollars to 29.56 million dollars
for the week, according to official figures released Saturday by
the Reserve Bank of India (RBI).
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the jump in reserves, which included gold
and special drawing rights, primarily to "sterilization" efforts
by the RBI, India's central bank.
</P>
<P>
RBI said in its Weekly Statistical Supplement that since the
end of last December, foreign currency assets had gone up by 2.609
billion dollars and total reserves increased by 2.479 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, gold reserves went down by 11 million dollars to 2.96
billion dollars by April 1, the supplement showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
