<HEADLINE> Paper Says Philippines Not to Restructure Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Finance has
decided to shelve the planned restructuring of some 1.8 billion
U.S. dollars worth of Philippine debt instruments being traded in
the international bond markets.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Bulletin Sunday quoted Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu as saying that there was no need to reopen anymore the
bonds since the government has already fully covered all its
financing requirements of this year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the declining interest rates abroad, Espiritu dismissed
the idea of reopening of the country's outstanding bonds aimed at
issuing new tenors at a lower yield to save on interest cost.
</P>
<P>
The planned restructuring of these loans will eventually add up
to the outstanding debt stock of the national government, which
stood at more than 46 billion dollars in the third quarter of last
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not doing it anymore. It will result in higher
(external) obligations for the national government," the secretary
said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government issued 1.3 billion dollars worth of
sovereign bonds in the international bond markets in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no more commercial loans. We have covered our
foreign financing requirements for 1999," Espiritu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
