<HEADLINE> Thailand to Introduce Subsistence Allowance Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Thai authorities will
introduce a program to provide job losers with subsistence
allowance and retraining in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Government agencies, including the employment and skills
development departments of the Labor and Social Welfare Ministry
and Office of the Civil Service Commission, are looking into
suitable schemes, and public hearings would be held once the study
was complete, reported the Bangkok Post on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A royal decree to put the scheme in effect under the provision
of the Social Security Act would probably be issued in 2001, SSO
deputy secretary-general Somkiat Chayasriwon was quoted by the
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
More staff and additional equipment would be needed if the
scheme was to be implemented. Under the scheme, people out of work
would be paid a subsistence allowance for a certain period,
Somkiat said.
</P>
<P>
They would be required to register as unemployed with the
Employment Department. While waiting for a suitable job, they
would have to undergo training at the Skills Development
Department.
</P>
<P>
Employers and employees would be required to make equal
contributions to the job security fund, not exceeding five percent
of the workers' monthly salary.
</P>
<P>
To benefit from the scheme, a worker must have made at least
six contributions to the fund during a period of 15 months.
</P>
<P>
A worker sacked for dishonesty, negligence or criminal offense,
or violation of regulations would not be entitled to benefits.
</P>
<P>
Nikom Chantaravithoon, a labor expert, said a job security
scheme was even more necessary in times of economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
Similar schemes operate successfully in many countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
