<HEADLINE> Telecom Deal Excites Foreign Telecom Providers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A recent framework agreement
signed between AT&AMP;T and the Shanghai Municipal government has sent
a promising sign to foreign telecom service providers about easier
access to the nation's telecom market.
</P>
<P>
The deal enabled a foreign partner for the first time to
provide telecom services in China.
</P>
<P>
A joint venture will be set up under the agreement operating
value-added telecom services in Shanghai Pudong New Area, marking
a genuine breakthrough in opening up China's telecommunications
sector.
</P>
<P>
"The telecommunications service market must open up further to
the outside world and the joint venture with AT&AMP;T marks the first
step in this trend," said Wu Jichuan, the country's information
industry minister.
</P>
<P>
After the large price cuts in the telecom service sector last
month, the telecom administration is losing no time in drafting
the country's first telecommunications regulation, which is
expected to be released by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts said the government's active measures,
including the break-up of the China Telecom monopoly, are aimed at
normalizing the rapid development of the telecom industry and
preparing for the opening-up of the world's largest telecom market.
</P>
