<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka, India Talk to Salvage Free Trade Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka and India are
continuing talks to salvage the bilateral free trade agreement
signed last December, the official Sunday Observer reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said India appears to be trying to link Sri Lanka's
tea export quota with exports of its own goods like Indian
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
"They have asked for concessions on exports of vehicles," the
newspaper quoted an official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The free trade deal, under which both countries progressively
cut tariffs, was to have come into effect on March 1, but hit
snags when India at the last moment withdrew concessions on the
export of Ceylon tea.
</P>
<P>
A team of Indian officials held talks here recently to try to
work out a compromise on the free trade pact on which both
countries have placed so much expectations.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka had been hoping that duty free exports of Ceylon tea
would be allowed by India.
</P>
<P>
However, New Delhi offered a tea export quota of 5 million
kilos or 10 million U.S. dollars worth of tea, whichever is
reached first within a specified time frame, subject to a
50-percent duty.
</P>
<P>
Besides, India also proposed quotas on garments, the island's
main industrial export product, which earlier was to be placed on
a "negative list" of products on which no tariff concessions will
be given.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka then asked for a much bigger tea export quota and
hopes to reach a compromise on the volume, the report said,
quoting official sources.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka expects to export about 10-15 million kilos of Ceylon
tea to India annually.
</P>
<P>
It also hopes to make up for the loss of a big chunk of exports
to the Commonwealth of Independence States, the biggest buyer of
Ceylon tea, after the economic crisis caused by the devaluation of
the rouble last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
