<HEADLINE> Malaysia Names Hendra-like Virus Nipah Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has named the new
Hendra-like virus the Nipah virus after the name of a village
where the new virus was first discovered.
</P>
<P>
The killer virus, named after Kampung Sungai Nipah in the
southern state of Negeri Sembilan, has so far claimed dozens of
lives in pig farming areas in the state.
</P>
<P>
Local and foreign experts have determined that 88 of the
victims of viral encephalitis had the Nipah virus first discovered
on March 15 by Chua Kaw Bing, a researcher at University Malaya's
Medical Microbiology Department, while 11 had both the Nipah virus
and the Japanese Encephalitis (JE) virus.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the naming of the new virus in Seremban, the state's
capital Saturday, Malaysian Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said
that the new virus has now been reaffirmed by the findings of the
Center for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta which
recently conducted a study on viral encephalitis patients from
Negeri Sembilan, Leading national daily New Straits Times reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Our concern now is the Nipah virus, which is the first such
manifestation in the world. We are now trying to develop a
specific test for the new virus," the minister was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Chua said the government's priority is to contain the Nipah
virus while efforts to check the spread of the JE viral infection
would be continued.
</P>
<P>
He said infection caused by the JE virus or the Nipah virus is
still considered viral encephalitis as the viruses attack the
brain cells.
</P>
<P>
All soldiers involved in pig culling operations have been
ordered to undergo blood screening to ensure they are free of the
JE or Nipah virus infections.
</P>
<P>
The order issued by the health minister followed the admission
of an soldier involved in the pig culling operation into the
Seremban Hospital for suspected viral encephalitis infection on
April 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
