<HEADLINE> Fish, Prawn Trading Companies Closed in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A number of fish and prawn trading
companies operating along Myanmar's southwestern coastal areas
have closed due to unhealthy competition, according to the latest
issue of the local Myanmar Business News magazine.
</P>
<P>
Intense bidding among these companies have led to opportunistic
situation in the area, said the report, adding there remains only
a single company in the area carrying out export business to five
countries.
</P>
<P>
The fishery sector, which is the third largest foreign exchange
earner after agriculture and forestry, earned 167 million U.S.
dollars in the 1997-98 fiscal year by exporting over 74,000 tons
of fish and prawn.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar plans to build an international-level fish
wholesale center in the country to expand its sea fish and prawn
market.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is also boosting its fish and prawn production by
allowing joint venture operation between the government and
private and foreign entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, foreign investment in the
sector, which came from Bangladesh, China, Germany, Japan and
Thailand, amounted to 275.35 million U.S. dollars in 18 projects
at the end of 1998, out of the 7.1 billion dollars' total foreign
investment in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
