<HEADLINE> 3 Killed in Shoot-out on Thai-Myanmar Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A police source confirmed the
press reports on Sunday that three people were killed in a
shoot-out between anti-drug squads and a narcotic-trafficking gang
on the Thai-Myanmar border.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out occurred in Pang Vour village in Chiang Rai,
northern Thailand on Saturday, killing one Thai police officer and
two ethnic Lahu drug-smugglers, said the source who refused to be
named.
</P>
<P>
Police officer Sanan Sasom was shot in the chest during an
operation to arrest armed drug smugglers who came to the village
to demand payment from certain individuals who had purchased
amphetamines from them, according to the Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Police confiscated one AK-47 automatic rifle and scores of
bullets after the armed group fled to the mountains.
</P>
<P>
An area leading to the Myanmar border has been shut off and
more officers were called in to help track the armed
drug-traffickers.
</P>
<P>
This was the latest in a series of violent clashes between the
Thai authorities and various Meanness armed groups that have
rocked the border, forcing the Thai authorities to close down some
border checkpoints to contain the violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
