<HEADLINE> Japanese Voters Begin Casting Ballots in Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The first round of local elections
began early Sunday throughout Japan.
</P>
<P>
The elections, the first since Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi took office last summer, encompass Tokyo and 11 other
prefectural governorships, the Sapporo mayoral race as well as
posts in 44 prefectural assemblies and 11 major municipal
assemblies.
</P>
<P>
The results of the elections in Tokyo and 11 other prefectures
are expected to be known by midnight Sunday, while seats of 44 of
Japan's 47 prefectural assemblies and of 11 major city assemblies
would be decided by early Monday.
</P>
<P>
As a prelude to the election of the House of Representative,
scheduled to be held in October next year, performance of
political parties during the elections will likely affect their
future and Japan's political landscape.
</P>
<P>
A total of 58 candidates are vying in the 12 governorship races,
with 19 of them running for the Tokyo governor.
</P>
<P>
Voters are choosing among 4,013 people filing for the 2,669
seats in the 44 prefectural assemblies.
</P>
<P>
The second round of the key local polls -- for mayors and
assembly members of small cities, wards, towns and villages --
will be held on April 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
