<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Hints at Constitutional Amendment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
has hinted at a possible constitutional amendment to save the
state the burden of having to arrange for overseas Thais to vote
in national elections.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's Bangkok Post quoted Chuan as confirming on Saturday
that he had discussed the matter with some election commission
members due to poor interest among overseas Thais in their
election rights.
</P>
<P>
The commission has yet to officially propose its idea to the
government.
</P>
<P>
The number of people who registered for the voting rights was
so small that some members believed the government should not
waste money to arrange for them to vote, Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
Some commission members were said to have been unhappy about
the low response from the overseas Thais to a commission
requirement for them to register for the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
"My understanding is that the number of people who wish to vote
is so small that the commission feels it may not be worthwhile
spending money on such votes," Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
The commission has reported that there are altogether 757,504
Thais in 78 countries worldwide who are eligible to vote. However,
only 16,309 have registered to exercise their voting rights until
April 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that the government may have to invest 1
billion baht (27 million U.S. dollars) to enable overseas Thais to
vote in the general elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
