<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100GMT, April 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- A sit-in protest against the NATO air strikes over
Yugoslavia was staged Saturday outside the main gate of the U.S.
Spangdahlem military base in west Germany.
</P>
<P>
About 50 demonstrators carrying banners demanding an immediate
end to the air raids blocked the road until late afternoon.
Spangdahlem, in the state of Rhineland palatinate, is the biggest
U.S. air force base in Europe. (Germany-Protest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer Saturday
proposed a foreign minister meeting on Kosovo crisis by the seven
western industrial nations (G7) with Russia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is not to placate Russia, but to accept Russia with
earnest as a partner to solve the crisis, Fischer told the
Deutschlandfunk radio. (Germany-G8-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- A NATO spokesman said here Saturday that poor
weather had some impact on NATO air strikes in Yugoslavia over the
last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
NATO military spokesman K. Freytag told a news briefing that
the weather "hindered us significantly and affected our operation".
One group of combat aircraft flew and further three were canceled
due to the weather, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also confirmed that a radio relay facility near
Pristina was destroyed among the strategic targets hit by NATO
during Friday night and early Saturday morning. (NATO-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA) confirmed on Saturday
its rejection of last week's draft declaration on the Good Friday
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Senior representatives said they were "unimpressed" by the
efforts of British and Irish Governments to advance the Northern
Ireland peace process, according to BBC report. The news is a
serious blow to hopes of achieving a breakthrough on the thorny
issue of arms decommissioning when talks resume on Tuesday. (UK-
IRA-Peace) 
