<HEADLINE> U.S. Expert Says China's IPR Protection Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- An expert from the United States
said that China's protection of intellectual property rights has
made substantial progress, according to Business Weekly today.
</P>
<P>
"China's Trademark Law has reached an extremely high level,"
Frederick W. Mostert, president of the U.S.-based International
Trademark Association, told the paper.
</P>
<P>
"I was told that China is developing a trademark dilution law.
This is a very advanced field even in world terms," said Frederick,
who led a delegation of U.S. lawyers and legal practitioners
specializing in intellectual property to China earlier this month
to discuss trademark and intellectual property issues with Chinese
officials and scholars.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out some famous Chinese trademarks have
been registered in overseas markets by foreign companies due to
the enterprises' lack of sense of trademark rights.
</P>
<P>
On this, an official of the China Intellectual Property
Society said that the Trademark Law is expected to be revised soon
to fight against trademark infringements.
</P>
<P>
He stressed China's access to the World Trade Organization
would help strengthen its protection of intellectual property
rights. 
