<HEADLINE> China to Invest 250 Billion Yuan in Railway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- China will invest 250 billion
yuan in railway construction during the five years ending 2002, an
official with the Ministry of Railways has announced.
</P>
<P>
Cao Qing, director of the development and planning department
of the ministry, said that by 2002, massive railway construction
will extend China's railway lines beyond 70,000 km.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is racing against time planning an
expressway linking Beijing and Shanghai, China's most economically
vibrant city, adding that hopefully the construction of this
expressway will begin sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
The official said that when the five-year plan is completed,
the mountainous Southwest China region will have easy access to
the coast, facilitating the region's foreign trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The newly built railway lines will also enable coastal regions
to obtain abundant coal resources easily from north China, easing
its energy shortage.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that by November last year, China had
attracted 5.2 billion U.S. dollars in loans from international
monetary organizations and foreign governments for railway
construction, and that 218 foreign-funded companies were involved
in the railway sector, including 257 million U.S. dollars in
direct foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
