<HEADLINE> Chongqing Benefits From New Economic Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing has benefited greatly
from the government policy to stimulate the economy by increasing
investments in infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
The central government initiated a new 1998 strategy to spur
the sluggish economy resulting from the negative impact of last
summer's record flooding and lingering financial turmoil in
various parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, a municipality placed under direct central
government administration in 1997, recorded negative income growth
for rural laborers in the first three quarters of 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, Chongqing has been one of the major beneficiaries of
central government economic policies in place since the fourth
quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
Rural laborers have found new jobs in government-funded
infrastructure projects in various sectors, including water
conservancy, communications, environmental protection, the
construction of state-owned grain storage facilities and housing
for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attribute the sharp increase in demand for
laborers to increased investments by central and local governments.
</P>
<P>
Rising incomes have in turn increased demand for consumer goods
in Chongqing's rural markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
