<DOCNO> XIE19990411.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Private Firms Gain Freer Access to Foreign Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- China's private businesses are
expected to play a greater role in China's drive to absorb foreign
investment thanks to a policy environment that is better than ever,
reported Business Weekly today.
</P>
<P>
To this end, a group of private companies would be first
allowed to attend the third China Fair for International
Investment and Trade this year, regarded as the most important
event for attracting foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
"The move indicates that the central government is gradually
loosening its grip on cooperation between Chinese private
enterprises and foreign investors," said He Maochun, deputy
director of the World Trade Research Department of the Chinese
Academy of International Trade and Economic Co-operation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Another MOFTEC official said that encouraging private companies
to co-operate with foreign businesses complies with the trend of
diversification in the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
China's biggest city, Shanghai, is expected to launch a new
policy incentive, under which all kinds of standardized private
companies, as long as foreign investment does not exceed 50
percent of their own capital, will be permitted to co-operate with
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
In the past, however, various restrictions on the private
sector allowed a small number of such businesses to attract
foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
Only around 400 private companies in Shanghai co-operated with
foreign investors by the end of February, accounting for 0.4
percent of the city's total number of private companies.
</P>
<P>
But the situation is improving, particularly following the
raising of the legal status of the private sector in the newly
revised Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"In some respects, foreign companies will find it easier to
launch co-operative projects with China's private companies than
with state-owned ones, thanks to their similarities in management
regimes," according to Ma Yu, director of the Foreign Investment
Research Department under the Chinese Academy of International
Trade and Economic Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Despite flexible operational mechanism, most private businesses
are still inferior to their state-owned counterparts in terms of
business size, capital resources and sales networks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
