<HEADLINE> China's Medicine Reform Advances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The medical system reform
starting last year in China aims to provide a fair competitive
environment for State-owned and foreign-funded medical enterprise,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
the ongoing reform campaign, through which medical services are
intended to be made available to more people, obliges individuals
and their work units to shoulder medical expenses jointly, instead
of leaving the State to pick up the whole bill.
</P>
<P>
According to government officials, a list of medicines that may
be reimbursed will be issued in the near future. A committee
composed of specialists and scholars from all medical fields
nationwide will make out the list after a careful and scientific
assessment process.
</P>
<P>
Yu Mingde, pharmaceutical department director of the State
Economic and Trade Commission, said the reform had made people
more cautious in choosing medicines.
</P>
<P>
When buying regular medicines, people tend to favor products
manufactured by State enterprises, which have nearly the same
quality but much lower prices than those imported or made by
overseas-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The medical reform will force overseas-funded medical
enterprises to lower their prices according to production costs
and medical efficacy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the industry authority welcomes overseas medical
businesses to introduce new products with original curative
effects to the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
In addition, domestic medical enterprises must cut output and
stop low-level reconstruction to check price-cutting competition.
</P>
<P>
government officials predict that the sales volume of the
medical industry will rise from last year's 106.8 billion yuan (12.
9 billion US dollars), but at rate less than the eight percent in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
