<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Worst Over for Asian Property Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- After a year of great depression,
Asia's property market may begin its much-awaited recovery later
this year as interest rates are falling across the region and
currencies are stabilizing.
</P>
<P>
Although Asia's property market had been sluggish for many
years due to over-supply, the year of 1998 could be described as
its worst in a decade. Throughout Asia, real-estate markets saw an
unprecedented over-supply, which prompted big price falls in the
year.
</P>
<P>
During the year, home prices in Hong Kong fell 38 percent;
office prices in Jakarta fell 60 percent amid an economic collapse
and political unrest; office rents in Kuala Lumpur fell 30 percent
as the city's vacancy level climbed from 4 percent in 1997 to 16
percent. In Bangkok, office vacancies soared to nearly 30 percent.
In Singapore, retail rents plunged 23 percent as the vacancy level
nearly doubled.
</P>
<P>
The sluggish trend is expected to continue this year as
potential buyers are waiting for further prices slides,
real-estate experts said.
</P>
<P>
In a study on the prospects of the property market in 1999,
property consultancy firm Cuervo Far East Inc. said that there is
still a risk of owning and buying property nowadays on the
assumption that prices of real-estate are expected to come down
further.
</P>
<P>
"It is only a question of time when landlords lower prices to
attract a shrinking market whose demand has been dampened by the
crisis. We therefore expect prices, especially in certain sectors
and market segments with looming over-supply, to slide as
developers succumbed to market pressure," Cuervo said.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the downturn trend, the worst may be over for
the property market because interest rates throughout the region
are coming down and currencies are stable, or even appreciate
against the U.S. dollar now.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of last year, some Asian countries have cut
interest rates continuously to stimulate the economic recovery.
The Indonesian central Bank has brought the average interest rate
down to 34 percent now from 42 percent last December.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, interest rates have fallen to below 10 percent
from 25 percent a year ago. The Philippine central bank's
overnight lending rates were lowered to 12.5 percent from 30
percent at the peak of the financial crisis in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts expect the lower banking rates would trigger an
expansion of credit to potential home and office buyers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, governments of a number of Asian countries are
trying to revive the property market by allowing foreign investors
to own lands and property, pushing stubborn corporate deadbeats to
pay up or shut down.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the region's brighter economic picture could also pave
the way for the development of the property sector.
</P>
<P>
Last year, East Asian economies experienced their first
contraction in the past decade, but most of them, like South
Korea, Thailand, Malaysia and the Philippines, could achieve a
1-3.5 percent growth this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the quicker-than-expected recovery may push
banks to write off bad loans owned by the property sector and help
them get back to normal business.
</P>
<P>
With the economic recovery later this year, real-estate prices
are likely to become stable and start to soar in the last quarter,
they predicted.
</P>
<P>
"Last year was really bad, but there is already an indication
that business will be better (starting this year)," said Susan
Romero, vice president for marketing of a Philippine property
development company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
