<HEADLINE> UK Sends Aircraft Carrier to Adriatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) - Britain said on Saturday it was
sending an aircraft carrier to the Adriatic to strengthen NATO's
air strikes against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
"We can confirm that HMS Invincible is being deployed to the
Adriatic to help the NATO effort to stop President Milosevic's
offensive against the Kosovo Albanians," a Reuters report quoted a
Ministry of Defence official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This is all part of tightening the screw on Milosevic," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Invincible carries seven jets and nine helicopters and
packs a wide range of firepower. It will join the British
nuclear-powered submarine HMS Splendid, which has been firing
cruise missiles at targets in Yugoslavia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
NATO already has two aircraft carriers in the Adriatic: the
United States has sent the Theodore Roosevelt and France has
deployed the Foch.
</P>
<P>
No decision had been taken to send extra British troops to the
Balkans, said the official. But units were on standby in case they
were needed to help the humanitarian aid effort or enforce any
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Prime Minister Tony Blair repeatedly dismissed
speculation that NATO would send ground troops to fight their way
into Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
